@NODE LEOTUNE "LeoTune - Introduction to the fortune cookie program"

	  @{b}LeoTune@{ub}
	1995-02-10

LeoTune is a fortune cookie program. The idea is that every time you invoke LeoTune, it randomly gives you a short thought from it's database. Although LeoTune is downwards compatible with the most common fortune file format, it can do much more.

The fortune cookie database is a simple ascii file where you may add your own short thoughts or funny stories.

@{"Installation on an Amiga System   " link LT_INSTALL_AMIGA}
@{"Installation on a Unix System     " link LT_INSTALL_UNIX}
@{"Specifying the fortune cookie file" link LT_SPECIFY_COOKIE}
@{"Creating a fortune cookie file    " link LT_CREATE_COOKIE}
@{"Creating the fortune index files  " link LT_CREATE_INDEX}
@{"Complete command option list      " link LT_COMMAND_OPTIONS}
@{"Word wrapped fortune commands     " link LT_WW_COMMANDS}
@{"Program history                   " link LT_HISTORY}

This package does include the source of the program as well as an Amiga compatible binary file. You may compile your own version on any computer system if you have an ANSI C compliant compiler available. However, if the character set your OS uses is not compatible with the ANSI / ISO LATIN 1 character set (has multiple EOL characters like MS-DOS & VMS), LeoTune will probably not work.
@ENDNODE


@NODE LT_INSTALL_AMIGA "LeoTune - Installation on an Amiga System"

@{b}Installation on an Amiga system@{ub}

Move the LeoTune executable file somewhere on your default path.
@ENDNODE


@NODE LT_INSTALL_UNIX "LeoTune - Installaton on a Unix System"

@{b}Installation on a Unix system@{ub}

Compile LeoTune. With gcc it is done like this:
51% @{i}gcc -ansi LeoTune.c -o leotune@{ui}
52% @{i}strip leotune@{ui}

You may also try to compile LeoTune simply by saying @{i}make leotune@{ui}. I have included a standard Unix Makefile with this package.
@ENDNODE


@NODE LT_SPECIFY_COOKIE "LeoTune - Specifying the fortune cookie file"

@{b}Specifying the fortune cookie file@{ub}

If you just want to quickly test LeoTune (and you have compiled it if you are on a non-Amiga system (see @{"Installation on a Unix system" link LT_INSTALL_UNIX}), type the following lines:
@{i}leotune -i LeoTunes
leotune LeoTunes@{ui}

As a default, LeoTune tries to read its fortune file from the file called @{i}Fortunes:LeoTunes@{ui}. This is a very Amiga specific name, but no worry, Unix (and multi-user Amiga system) users:

If LeoTune finds an environmental variable called @{i}HOME@{ui}, it tries to read the fortune file from @{i}$(HOME)/text/LeoTunes@{ui}.

If you don't like these defaults, you may define an environmental variable called @{i}LEOTUNEDIR@{ui}, and LeoTune will try to read its file from @{i}$(LEOTUNEDIR)/LeoTunes@{ui}. You may add a trailing "/" to the directory name (or a ":" on the Amiga), but it is not required.

If you still aren't satisfied, you may define the fortune file and its path as defined later in this document as a @{"command line option" link LT_COMMAND_OPTIONS} for LeoTune (like we did in the example above).
@ENDNODE


@NODE LT_CREATE_COOKIE "LeoTune - Creating a fortune cookie file"

@{b}Creating a fortune cookie file@{ub}

The fortune cookie file is of a very simple format: 8-bit ISO 8859-1 (Latin 1) as used in Amiga OS, newer Unix systems and MS Windows. Two fortunes are separated by a line with only '%%' or '##' on it. For instance, below is a simple fortune file with three fortune cookies.

This is the first fortune.
%%
And this is the second one.
And way longer it is than was the first one.
##
Yoda the Jedi-master always strangely backwards talked but never any
spelling errors made. Selective he was in wrongly speaking.
%%

You probably want to name your fortune database file @{i}LeoTunes@{ui}, and put it in a directory you specified earlier (look at @{"Specifying the fortune database file" link LT_SPECIFY_COOKIE}).

I have included a small example fortune cookie file in this directory surprisingly called @{"LeoTunes" link LeoTunes/MAIN}.


@{b}About the Fortune Ending Characters@{ub}

As you have already noticed, a fortune can end in two different ways. Why?

The '%%' ending is the traditional and universally adopted standard separator of fortunes. LeoTune treats fortunes like this as already formatted, and it will simply display them just as they were in the fortune file.

However, the new '##' ending is another matter. By ending your fortune with this string you tell LeoTune it can handle the word wrapping for you. So, you may write as long lines you wish, and LeoTune will format them for you. You may also tell LeoTune to display the fortunes with different widths depending on your terminal (see @{"Command options" link LT_COMMAND_OPTIONS}). With word wrapped fortunes you may also use several @{"word wrapped fortune commands" link LT_WW_COMMANDS}. I strongly encourage the use of this new format I just invented.
@ENDNODE


@NODE LT_CREATE_INDEX "LeoTune - Creating the fortune index files"

@{b}Creating the fortune index files@{ub}

Before you may ask LeoTune to show one of the fortunes, you must ask it to create two index files. This is done by typing @{i}leotune -i@{ui}. LeoTune will announce how many fortunes it found and inserted to the index files. It will also tell you how many new indexes were created.

After this you are ready to go: just type @{i}leotune@{ui} and have fun. And, remember, every time you touch the fortune cookie file, you must run LeoTune with the @{i}-i@{ui} option.
@ENDNODE


@NODE LT_COMMAND_OPTIONS "LeoTune - A complete command option list"

@{b}A complete command option list@{ub}

Every command option has a synonym to make LeoTune compatible with both Unix and Amiga command option naming conventions.

-h	Shows a short credit and help page with all the commands and
?	their meanings listed.

-i	Creates the two LeoTune fortune index files. The first one
index	includes all the fortune cookies, and the second one only
	those with mostly 4 lines of not more than 79 characters each.
	The latter index file is mainly meant to be used to autocreate
	short Unix mail signatures.

-s	Normally LeoTune shows one blank line before and after the
short	fortune cookie. This option inhibits that.

-4	Shows a "signature" fortune with mostly 4 lines of not more
sig	than 79 characters each. This option will force the width of
	word wrapped fortunes to 79 columns. This option is meant to
	be used to create fortunes that follows the official signature
	netiquette as used in the UseNet community. To create a UseNet
	signature you probably also want to use the -s option.

-7	Convert the following characters: "éüĺäöÉÜĹÄÖ" to their 7-bit
iso11	Iso 11 equivalents: "`~}{|\@^][\\". All the other 8-bit
	characters are converted to question marks. This is a very
	Finnish option and may not be of much use elsewhere.

-t @{i}x@{ui}	Shows a specific fortune index @{i}x@{ui} where @{i}x@{ui} must be an integer
tune @{i}x@{ui}	between 1 and the amount of fortunes in the fortune file. If
	-4 is also defined, the fortune will be taken from the
	signature fortune database.

-g @{i}x@{ui}	Shows all fortunes that include the specified string @{i}x@{ui}. This
grep @{i}x@{ui}	option will always turn the -4 option off and the -s option
	on. The string @{i}x@{ui} is case-insensitive.

-G @{i}x@{ui}	Like -g / grep, but case-sensitive. So, @{i}Leopold@{ui} will be a
GREP @{i}x@{ui}	different thing from @{i}leopold@{ui} or @{i}LEOPOLD@{ui}.

-w @{i}x@{ui}	Defines the maximum width of word-wrapped fortunes. The default
width @{i}x@{ui}	is 79 or whatever you have set in your environmental variable
	$COLUMNS. This option will have no effect if the -4 option is
	used.

filenam	If you provide a filename, that file will be used as the
	fortune cookie base file instead of the default file.
@ENDNODE


@NODE LT_WW_COMMANDS "LeoTune - Word wrapped fortune commands"

@{b}Word wrapped fortune commands@{ub}

A fortune that ends with a line that consists only of '##' is considered to be a word wrapped fortune by LeoTune, i.e. LeoTune will take care of word wrapping instead of you.


@{b}Newline@{ub}

A Newline character is the equivalent to a whitespace. However, any n number of successive Newlines (where n > 2) is considered as n-1 Newlines.


@{b}Escape Commands@{ub}

The backslash character '\\' is considered as a command escape character and always begins a command. If the character(s) after the escape character can not be recognized as a command, the escape character is simply disregarded.

\\>	Tells LeoTune to indent every line to the column the cursor is
	currently on until the next Newline command is encountered.
	The indent commands do not nest.

\\<	Tells LeoTune to unindent the text indented with \\>.

\\\\	Displays a backslash character '\\'.


@{b}An Example of Using Word Wrap Commands@{ub}

So, let's say you have the following fortune in your fortune file (the quoted lines begin with '-> '):

-> Hofstadterin laki:
->
-> -- \\>Projektin valmistumien vie aina enemmän aikaa kuin olit
-> arvioinut. Tämä pätee myös silloin, kun olet ottanut
-> Hofstadterin lain huomioon.
->
-> That was Finnish, you know :-)
-> ##

If you now invoke LeoTune first with the option @{"-i" link LT_CREATE_INDEX} and then with the option @{"-w 40" link LT_COMMAND_OPTIONS}, you'll get a following fortune displayed:

-> Hofstadterin laki:
-> -- Projektin valmistumien vie aina
->    enemmän aikaa kuin olit arvioinut.
->    Tämä pätee myös silloin, kun olet
->    ottanut Hofstadterin lain huomioon.
-> That was Finnish, you know :-)


@{b}Suggestions?@{ub}

This concept of using control characters in a fortune file is all new. If you have suggestions of important new control characters you'd like LeoTune to handle, please let me know. @{"I'll" link AUTHOR} do what I can.
@ENDNODE


@NODE LT_HISTORY "LeoTune - History"

@{b}History@{ub}

4.14

961119	17612	Minor changes to source to get Leotune to compile
