@NODE AMIGAGUIDE "AmigaGuide - All Leopold-Soft knows about it"

	@{b}AmigaGuide - All @{"Leopold-Soft" link AUTHOR} knows about it@{ub}

This is @{u}not@{uu} a comprehensive and official description of the AmigaGuide format. This is just what I have figured out with the kind help of AmigaWorld (Feb-94) and my exploration of AmigaGuide documents. All terminology (like @{i}inline commands@{ui}) is invented by me. If there is an official AmigaGuide document specification floating around somewhere in the net, I'd like to hear about it.


AmigaGuide documents consist of case-insensitive @{"command lines" link AG_COMMAND_LINES} and @{"nodes" link AG_NODES}. A @{"node" link AG_NODES} contains 8-bit Latin-1 (= ISO 8859-1) @{"text" link AG_TEXT}, @{"inline commands" link AG_INLINE_COMMANDS} which of the most important is the @{"link" link AG_LINKS} command..

Every document @{u}must@{uu} begin with a @{"command line" link AG_COMMAND_LINES}, which says @{i}\@DATABASE "MyFile.guide"@{ui}. This line will identify the file as an AmigaGuide text file.
@ENDNODE




@NODE AG_NODES "AmigaGuide - Nodes"

	@{b}AmigaGuide Nodes@{ub}

AmigaGuide Nodes begin with the following @{"command line" link AG_COMMAND_LINES}:
\@NODE F_ZAPPA "The Frank Zappa discography"

F_ZAPPA is the name of the node. The text inside the quote characters will be shown as the window title for the node.

The nodes end with the @{"command line" link AG_COMMAND_LINES}:
\@ENDNODE

Inside a node you may type standard 8-bit Latin 1 (= ISO 8859-1) @{"text" link AG_TEXT}.

You may create a @{"link" link AG_LINKS} to this node by adding a @{"LINK inline command" link AG_INLINE_COMMANDS} like this in any node:
The death of \@{"Frank Zappa" link F_ZAPPA} really struck me hard.

As a default, a node called @{i}MAIN@{ui} is considered to be the Table of Contents node, although this can be changed with the @{"command line TOC" link AG_COMMAND_LINES}.
@ENDNODE



@NODE AG_LINKS "AmigaGuide - Links"

	@{b}AmigaGuide Links@{ub}

AmigaGuide links are links to other @{"nodes" link AG_NODES} in the same file or to external files.

The external files may be of any type that the Amiga OS's datatypes support: IFF ILBM images, IFF 8SVX sound samples, plain Ascii files (not AmigaGuide documents), animations and much else. They may also be links to AREXX scripts and some even more curious things.

The basic form of the link command is like this:
@{b}\@{"@{ub}mylink@{b}" LINK @{ub}MY_NODE@{b}}@{ub}
"mylink" is a text string, which AmigaGuide will present as a press button. MY_NODE is the name of the node you want the link to point to.

The external format #1 is like this:
@{b}\@{"@{ub}mylink@{b}" LINK @{ub}MyPicture.ilbm@{b}}@{ub}
This will create a link to the specified file.

If the file is a plain Ascii file, you may also use the external format #2:
@{b}\@{"@{ub}mylink@{b}" LINK @{ub}MySource.c 25@{b}}@{ub}
When pressed this link will show the file MySource.c and locate it to line #25.

If the file is an AmigaGuide document, you may use the external format #3:
@{b}\@{"@{ub}mylink@{b}" LINK @{ub}PathFile/MY_NODE@{b}}@{ub}
When pressed this will show MY_NODE from the file PathFile.


For some strange reason external links don't seem to work on XPK (2.4) compressed disk partitions.
@ENDNODE



@NODE AG_COMMAND_LINES "AmigaGuide - Command Lines"

	@{b}AmigaGuide Command Lines@{ub}

AmigaGuide command lines may be placed anywhere in an AmigaGuide document with the exception of \@DATABASE, which must be the first command on the first line.

A command line must start with the "\@"-character.

All commands are case-insensitive. They are capitalized in this document only to emphasize them.

All commands not recognized are treated like comments. This way an older version of AmigaGuide will not show any error messages when trying to read formatting from a newer version document.

The command lines marked with an asterisk "*" are handled by @{"GuideCat" link GUIDECAT}.

The commands (@{"I" link AUTHOR} know of) are as follows:

@{b}\@\$VER:MyFile.guide 1.0 (04/22/94)@{ub}
An Amiga -specific version number string. This command is probably not handled as a command at all by AmigaGuide.

@{b}\@(C) "Copyright ©1994 Leopold-Soft"@{ub}
A copyright string. This command is probably not handled as a command at all by AmigaGuide.

@{b}\@AUTHOR "Henrik Herranen"@{ub}
An author string. This command is probably not handled as a command at all by AmigaGuide.

@{b}\@DATABASE "MyFile.guide"@{ub} *
Defines the name of the AmigaGuide file. This command @{u}must@{uu} be the first command in an AmigaGuide file. "MyFile.guide" is usually the same as the name of the file.

@{b}\@ENDNODE@{ub} *
Ends a @{"node" link AG_NODES}.

@{b}\@FONT fontname.font size@{ub}
Defines the font you want to use in the next node. For some reason using this command line will fail if you type it inside a node. At least this is true with the current version of AmigaGuide (40.1).
	As a rule of thumb I'd say you should not use excessively the \@FONT command, because Amiga users use very different kinds of Amigas with different display modes, and they have already set their preferences to properly show their favourite font.

@{b}\@INDEX INDEX_NODE@{ub}
Defines which node you want to be the index @{"node" link AG_NODES}. There is a button on the AmigaGuide window called @{i}Index@{ui}, which will be inactivated if this command is not used.

@{b}\@NEXT NEXT_NODE@{ub}
Defines which node to jump to if the user presses the @{i}"Browse >"@{ui} button in AmigaGuide. This command line must be placed immediately after a \@NODE (or \@PREV) command line.

@{b}\@NODE NODE_NAME "Window title"@{ub} *
defines a beginning of a @{"node" link AG_NODES}. Nodes do not nest (what kind of an idea would that be :-) ).

@{b}\@PREV PREV_NODE@{ub}
Defines which node to jump to if the user presses the @{i}"Browse <"@{ui} button in AmigaGuide. This command line must be placed immediately after a \@NODE (or \@NEXT) command line.

@{b}\@REM This line will demonstrate how a comment is made@{ub}
A comment line. This command is probably not handled as a command at all by AmigaGuide.

@{b}\@TOC TABLE_OF_CONTENTS_NODE@{ub}
This will define your Table of Contents @{"node" link AG_NODES}. The default Table of Contents -node is @{i}MAIN@{ui}.

@{b}\@WORDWRAP@{ub} *
This line tells AmigaGuide to take care of text wrapping. If you have defined this option, you may write lines as long as you wish and AmigaGuide will format them to fit on the user's AmigaGuide window. In my opinion you should always write your AmigaGuide documents with this option on. I have read that this command line may be somewhat incompatible with older versions of AmigaGuide.
@ENDNODE



@NODE AG_INLINE_COMMANDS "AmigaGuide - Inline Commands"

	@{b}AmigaGuide Inline Commands@{ub}

Inline commands may be inserted anywhere inside a @{"node" link AG_NODES}. They are recognized by their first two characters, "\@{". The latter character makes the inline commands distinguishable from @{"command lines" link AG_COMMAND_LINES} when they begin a line.

All commands are case-insensitive. They are capitalized in this document only to emphasize them.

All commands not recognized are treated like comments. This way an older version of AmigaGuide will not show any error messages when trying to read formatting from a newer version document.

The command lines marked with an asterisk (*) are handled by @{"GuideCat" link GUIDECAT}.

The commands (@{"I" link AUTHOR} know of) are as follows:

@{b}\@{"@{ub}text string@{b}" LINK @{ub}NODE_NAME@{b}}@{ub} *
Creates a @{"link" link AG_LINKS} to a @{"node" link AG_NODES}.

@{b}\@{B}@{ub} *
Turns bold on. @{b}This is an example of bold text.@{ub}

@{b}\@{BG @{i}COLOR@{ui}}@{ub} *
Selects a new color for text background. @{i}COLOR@{ui} is a keyword defined at the description of command \@{FG @{i}COLOR@{ui}}.

@{b}\@{FG @{i}COLOR@{ui}}@{ub} *
Selects a new color for text. @{i}COLOR@{ui} can be any of the following keywords:
- BACKGROUND is the default color of the backgroud (usually grey on an Amiga system and white on other systems). @{fg BACKGROUND}@{bg TEXT}This is an example of BACKGROUND color text on TEXT color background, which makes this effectively reverse text.@{fg TEXT}@{bg BACKGROUND}
- HIGHLIGHT selects the color the user has selected in his palette preferences as "Important text". @{fg HIGHLIGHT}This is an example of highlighted text.@{fg TEXT} @{bg HIGHLIGHT}This is an example of text with a highlighted background.@{bg BACKGROUND}
- TEXT is the default text color (usually black).

@{b}\@{I}@{ub} *
Turns italics on. @{i}This is an example of italic text.@{ui}

@{b}\@{U}@{ub} *
Turns underline on. @{u}This is an example of underlined text.@{uu}

@{b}\@{UB}@{ub} *
Turns bold off.

@{b}\@{UI}@{ub} *
Turns italics off.

@{b}\@{UU}@{ub} *
Turns underline off.
@ENDNODE



@NODE AG_TEXT "AmigaGuide - Text Blocks Inside Nodes"

	@{b}AmigaGuide Text Blocks Inside Nodes@{ub}

@{"Nodes" link AG_NODES} are filled with @{"inline commands" link AG_INLINE_COMMANDS} and text.

The text in a node is a superset of Ascii, 8-bit Latin 1 ( = ISO 8859-1 ) ( = ECMA 94 ) as used in Amigas, many newer Unix systems and MS Windows. It is @{u}not@{uu} the same font that is used in unstandardized systems like MS-DOS, Macs or Nexts.

Because the commands begin with a "@"-character, there is an escape key provided which prevents AmigaGuide from trying to guess the meaning of the following character. This allows you to write the letter \@ in your AmigaGuide documents. The escape character is "\\". This will lead to the following conversions:

This:	Displays this:
\\\@	\@
\\\\	\\
\\x	x
\\	(nothing at all)
@ENDNODE




